WEBVTT

00:07.474 --> 00:08.375
‐ Previously on
"The Betty Broderick Story"...

00:09.343 --> 00:10.878
‐ The number one thing

00:10.911 --> 00:12.980
I loved about you in
the beginning was how much you

00:13.013 --> 00:14.414
loved me and showed it.

00:14.448 --> 00:16.984
‐ I want to be
a responsible, sensitive

00:17.017 --> 00:18.519
husband, and father,

00:18.552 --> 00:21.588
a who will be missed
when he dies.

00:21.622 --> 00:22.422
‐ You make me forget
that I'm angry

00:22.456 --> 00:24.424
at the asshole and his whore,

00:24.458 --> 00:26.193
and if I'm not angry,
I'm not gonna make it.

00:26.226 --> 00:28.328
‐ She's not gonna kill
the golden goose, Richard.

00:28.362 --> 00:29.196
She just isn't.

00:29.229 --> 00:31.198
‐ I haven't
had anything my way.

00:31.231 --> 00:33.600
Daddy robbed me
of everything I had on earth!

00:33.634 --> 00:36.436
He ‐‐‐‐‐‐ your whole life
and my whole life!

00:36.470 --> 00:39.473
[overlapping
hostile chatter]

00:40.474 --> 00:43.043
‐ Crazy...
...the monster...

00:43.076 --> 00:46.046
‐ If you want to destroy me,
get it over and done with.

00:46.079 --> 00:47.981
‐ Mrs. Broderick is charged

00:48.015 --> 00:49.883
with two counts
of first‐degree murder.

00:49.917 --> 00:51.485
‐ We enter a plea
of not guilty

00:51.518 --> 00:52.753
and request a jury trial.

00:52.786 --> 00:53.787
‐ You are the most important
person I have

00:53.820 --> 00:57.124
in the whole universe,
bar absolutely none,

00:57.157 --> 00:59.092
and I'd be lost without you.

01:02.362 --> 01:04.731
[soft dramatic music]

01:04.765 --> 01:08.168
[ribbons rustling]

01:08.201 --> 01:10.971
I don't remember.

01:11.004 --> 01:12.406
I don't remember.

01:12.439 --> 01:13.907
‐ Do you remember telling
many people

01:13.941 --> 01:16.143
you dumped your kids off
at his house because

01:16.176 --> 01:18.478
if you couldn't be
Mrs. Dan Broderick,

01:18.512 --> 01:19.947
you weren't going
to take care of the kids.

01:19.980 --> 01:21.248
‐ Not those words.

01:21.281 --> 01:26.219
He had left me alone for months
with the rats and everything.

01:26.253 --> 01:28.422
He didn't offer any help.
I was overwhelmed.

01:28.455 --> 01:30.991
I wanted him to know
how hard the job was

01:31.024 --> 01:32.726
of taking care of these kids.

01:32.759 --> 01:34.828
I wanted him to be involved.

01:34.861 --> 01:36.029
‐ So you wanted to punish him?

01:36.063 --> 01:37.097
Make his life miserable

01:37.130 --> 01:40.267
by dumping four kids
in an empty home, full‐time.

01:40.300 --> 01:41.301
‐ If that is what
you want to say.

01:41.335 --> 01:43.437
‐ I'm asking you.
Remember?

01:43.470 --> 01:45.505
‐ Remember, he wasn't
talking about Linda,

01:45.539 --> 01:46.473
he wasn't talking
about divorce,

01:46.506 --> 01:48.508
he wouldn't mention
the word "separation,"

01:48.542 --> 01:49.443
he just needed his space.

01:49.476 --> 01:51.612
‐ So then why did you
dump the kids off?

01:51.645 --> 01:52.879
‐ Your Honor,
I'm going to object.

01:52.913 --> 01:54.014
Argumentative.

01:54.047 --> 01:56.850
If bringing your kids to
their father is dumping them,

01:56.883 --> 01:58.018
that's Ms. Wells' definition.

01:58.051 --> 02:00.253
‐ Rephrase the question.

02:00.287 --> 02:02.522
♪ ♪

02:02.556 --> 02:03.991
‐ Dear Mrs. Broderick,
I read the articles

02:04.024 --> 02:06.727
about you in the "Register"
and I had to write you.

02:06.760 --> 02:09.596
You have my understanding
and sympathy.

02:09.630 --> 02:11.632
I can personally relate
to the inability

02:11.665 --> 02:14.901
to find proper representation
if the spouse is prominent.

02:14.935 --> 02:18.772
‐ The fining system stopped
in December of 1986

02:18.805 --> 02:21.041
when a judge said
he could not do that.

02:21.074 --> 02:21.842
If you have a complaint,

02:21.875 --> 02:23.477
you must file
a contempt action.

02:23.510 --> 02:26.647
‐ I don't remember
about a contempt action,

02:26.680 --> 02:28.415
but I do know a judge said

02:28.448 --> 02:31.051
that Dan couldn't keep money
out of the check anymore.

02:31.084 --> 02:33.487
‐ At that time he was keeping
money out of your checks,

02:33.520 --> 02:35.922
he was paying you
voluntarily support.

02:35.956 --> 02:37.224
There was no court order

02:37.257 --> 02:38.592
ordering him
to pay you support.

02:38.625 --> 02:39.593
‐ Correct.

02:39.626 --> 02:42.396
‐ So if he really wanted
to be a jerk,

02:42.429 --> 02:45.732
he didn't have to
pay you anything.

02:45.766 --> 02:46.833
‐ Right.

02:46.867 --> 02:47.834
‐ Dear Mrs. Broderick,

02:47.868 --> 02:49.002
I've been watching you
on Court TV.

02:49.036 --> 02:50.003
When my husband left me,

02:50.037 --> 02:51.405
he was advised
to postpone the settlement

02:51.438 --> 02:56.343
until a change in the divorce
law to the infamous no‐fault.

02:56.376 --> 02:57.911
I was a sitting duck
and did not know it,

02:57.944 --> 02:59.146
just like you.

02:59.179 --> 03:03.316
‐ I would like to have marked
as a series of five checks,

03:03.350 --> 03:05.419
one, two, three, four, five,

03:05.452 --> 03:08.622
which appear to be written
on Broderick's accounts.

03:08.655 --> 03:10.157
People's 53.

03:10.190 --> 03:14.828
Can you, um, identify this
for us?

03:14.861 --> 03:16.963
‐ A check to me in July, 1985.

03:16.997 --> 03:20.133
‐ For how much?
‐ $3,000.

03:20.167 --> 03:22.569
‐ From whom?
‐ From Dan.

03:22.602 --> 03:25.205
‐ And did you put a little note
on the bottom of that?

03:25.238 --> 03:27.774
‐ Yes.
‐ What did you say?

03:27.808 --> 03:28.909
‐ "Thanks, sweetie."

03:28.942 --> 03:30.310
‐ Dear Betty,

03:30.343 --> 03:32.312
I saw you on the 11:00 news
and thought,

03:32.345 --> 03:35.882
"There but for the grace
of God go all of us

03:35.916 --> 03:38.719
"who have been stripped of our
life as we knew it

03:38.752 --> 03:42.222
"or thought it to be because
of the success of our husbands

03:42.255 --> 03:43.523
which we contributed to."

03:43.557 --> 03:46.793
‐ [laughs]
‐ "Or accomplished for them."

03:46.827 --> 03:49.196
‐ The fact is, Dan Broderick
was very close‐mouthed

03:49.229 --> 03:51.164
about the problems between you,
isn't that true?

03:51.198 --> 03:52.399
‐ Closed mouth to me, yes.

03:52.432 --> 03:53.934
‐ Close‐mouthed
to other people?

03:53.967 --> 03:55.335
‐ No.

03:55.368 --> 03:57.404
He told his family
and other people

03:57.437 --> 03:59.706
total untruths
about what was going on.

03:59.740 --> 04:02.542
Complete lies,
turning everything around.

04:02.576 --> 04:05.846
Denying anything with Linda,
leading everyone to believe

04:05.879 --> 04:07.814
black was white
and white was black.

04:07.848 --> 04:09.149
‐ I read
your recent interview.

04:09.182 --> 04:12.719
There are many people who
do not consider you crazy

04:12.753 --> 04:14.755
but who do understand
the possibility

04:14.788 --> 04:17.557
of being driven off‐balance
given the circumstances

04:17.591 --> 04:21.194
and degree of fear and stress
and emotional abuse.

04:21.228 --> 04:22.662
Have faith.

04:22.696 --> 04:25.031
‐ Did you talk around town
in 1985

04:25.065 --> 04:27.901
about problems between
you and Dan Broderick?

04:27.934 --> 04:30.971
‐ Sure I did.

04:31.004 --> 04:33.673
Sure I would've
been aghast at the...

04:33.707 --> 04:36.476
lying that had gone on
for so long.

04:39.579 --> 04:43.316
Finding out that Linda
had been in my house?

04:45.252 --> 04:47.621
Sure I said a lot of things
to people.

04:47.654 --> 04:48.522
‐ That was one of the reasons

04:48.555 --> 04:51.458
you started
to lose your friends.

04:51.491 --> 04:52.959
You didn't talk
about anything else

04:52.993 --> 04:55.395
other than your problems
with Dan Broderick, right?

04:55.428 --> 04:59.766
‐ I quit all the things
I belong to.

04:59.800 --> 05:00.801
I quit the things at school.

05:00.834 --> 05:02.536
I didn't want
to be around people

05:02.569 --> 05:03.870
when the only thing on my mind

05:03.904 --> 05:05.739
was the next court hearing,
the next trial,

05:05.772 --> 05:07.741
the next whatever.

05:07.774 --> 05:09.643
I was totally under siege

05:09.676 --> 05:12.779
whether I lost everyone
or everyone lost me.

05:15.282 --> 05:17.083
It didn't matter.

05:17.117 --> 05:20.253
[indistinct chatter]

05:25.692 --> 05:28.428
[laughs]

05:29.529 --> 05:31.298
‐ You went through
the kitchen,

05:31.331 --> 05:33.066
then the hallway
to the stairs.

05:33.099 --> 05:35.368
You went up the stairs.

05:35.402 --> 05:36.736
You knew at this point

05:36.770 --> 05:39.005
you had the gun
in your hand, correct?

05:39.039 --> 05:41.308
‐ Yes.

05:44.711 --> 05:47.981
I was looking for Dan
and I was very scared.

05:48.014 --> 05:50.750
‐ And you knew that his bedroom
was right off to the right

05:50.784 --> 05:53.920
at the top of the stairs,
correct?

05:55.789 --> 05:57.624
‐ Yes.

05:59.726 --> 06:01.528
‐ When you left
Dan Broderick's house,

06:01.561 --> 06:04.865
you said you drove
to Clairemont.

06:04.898 --> 06:06.933
Is that correct?

06:06.967 --> 06:10.604
‐ Uh, I‐‐I ended up
on a phone in Clairemont.

06:10.637 --> 06:12.706
I don't‐‐I don't know
how I got there.

06:12.739 --> 06:14.808
‐ Do you recall
where this phone was?

06:14.841 --> 06:18.445
‐ Someone asked.
Whoever I'd called.

06:18.478 --> 06:20.380
I looked around.

06:20.413 --> 06:24.084
I know Clairemont well
on a normal day.

06:24.117 --> 06:26.453
I had no idea where I was.

06:26.486 --> 06:28.855
Thank you
for your sweet note.

06:28.889 --> 06:30.924
Seems I have a lot
of people out there

06:30.957 --> 06:32.058
who sympathize with me.

06:32.092 --> 06:35.328
Also, I'm sorry for my
very inelegant stationary.

06:35.362 --> 06:37.564
‐ Willful needs intentional.

06:37.597 --> 06:40.500
Deliberate means
after careful thought.

06:40.533 --> 06:42.702
And the law is clear.

06:42.736 --> 06:45.739
There is not set amount
of days or minutes required

06:45.772 --> 06:48.642
for premeditation
to have been present.

06:48.675 --> 06:51.745
A cold, calculated judgment
may be arrived at

06:51.778 --> 06:54.080
in a very short period of time.

06:54.114 --> 06:56.616
‐ Thank you
for your sweet care package.

06:56.650 --> 06:58.385
No one out there has any idea

06:58.418 --> 07:00.520
of what I was forced
to endure.

07:00.553 --> 07:01.688
‐ It's important
to point out

07:01.721 --> 07:05.358
the fact the defendant
was feeling many emotions

07:05.392 --> 07:07.661
does not mean
she could not form

07:07.694 --> 07:10.196
a premeditated intent to kill.

07:10.230 --> 07:12.032
Feeling emotions
and making decisions

07:12.065 --> 07:13.133
are not mutually exclusive.

07:13.166 --> 07:16.736
In fact, we all do them
both at once all the time.

07:16.770 --> 07:20.173
‐ This is a story of legal
terrorism and corruption.

07:20.206 --> 07:22.008
Please keep in touch.

07:22.042 --> 07:24.344
Send me things to read and
thank you for the socks.

07:24.377 --> 07:26.846
Sincerely, Betty Broderick.

07:26.880 --> 07:29.950
‐ ...of the nature
of the allegations.

07:29.983 --> 07:34.020
I was surprised,
in disbelief,

07:34.054 --> 07:35.488
and again hurt...

07:35.522 --> 07:37.490
‐ You believe this shit?

07:37.524 --> 07:38.658
‐ Do I believe it?
Yes.

07:38.692 --> 07:41.361
‐ Guys on there before were
calling her "a woman scorned."

07:41.394 --> 07:44.397
Anita Hill.

07:44.431 --> 07:47.300
They call you that a lot, too.

07:47.334 --> 07:48.601
They like that one.

07:48.635 --> 07:50.437
‐ Being scorned just means

07:50.470 --> 07:52.505
other people think
you're worthless.

07:54.574 --> 07:56.042
Doesn't mean you are.

07:56.076 --> 07:57.944
‐ Is there any reason
to believe

07:57.978 --> 08:00.480
that further deliberations
would lead to verdict?

08:00.513 --> 08:01.715
‐ No.

08:01.748 --> 08:04.751
‐ Well, I've been instructed
that your deadlocked

08:04.784 --> 08:07.554
and that further deliberations
would be fruitless.

08:07.587 --> 08:09.155
Is this a true statement
from your point of view,

08:09.189 --> 08:10.223
Juror Number One?

08:10.256 --> 08:11.992
‐ I don't think
anybody thought

08:12.025 --> 08:13.226
she went over there
to kill herself,

08:13.259 --> 08:14.995
but I felt she was provoked.

08:15.028 --> 08:17.397
‐ Is this a true statement
from your point of view,

08:17.430 --> 08:18.498
Juror Number Seven?

08:18.531 --> 08:20.734
‐ Talking about him,
what kind of guy he was,

08:20.767 --> 08:23.803
putting him on trial,
I think that worked.

08:23.837 --> 08:24.871
It's probably why
we got hung up.

08:24.904 --> 08:27.073
‐ Is this a true statement
from your point of view,

08:27.107 --> 08:28.274
Juror Number Ten?

08:28.308 --> 08:29.809
‐ Yes, Your Honor.

08:29.843 --> 08:31.277
Every human
has a breaking point.

08:31.311 --> 08:33.480
With humans or any animal,

08:33.513 --> 08:35.582
you push 'em to that point,
they're gonna bite back.

08:35.615 --> 08:37.083
I'll be honest,

08:37.117 --> 08:39.452
I was disappointed they
couldn't argue self‐defense

08:39.486 --> 08:41.087
on the grounds
that she was abused.

08:41.121 --> 08:44.791
Her mind was battered‐‐
emotionally battered.

08:44.824 --> 08:47.527
They should change the laws
to protect women like she was,

08:47.560 --> 08:49.095
that's what I thought.

08:49.129 --> 08:53.967
After I heard everything,
what took her so long?

08:55.035 --> 08:57.937
[upbeat music]

08:57.971 --> 09:02.609
♪ ♪

09:08.548 --> 09:08.948
‐ 50 letters like that.

09:10.083 --> 09:12.819
75 the week before the
"Ladies' Home Journal" article.

09:12.852 --> 09:16.022
But now, they're from all over.
Philippines, Australia.

09:16.056 --> 09:19.526
They send me money, candy,
cigarettes, from one article.

09:19.559 --> 09:20.760
How can this not be great
for us?

09:20.794 --> 09:24.798
‐ It is, but you just can't
let it make you too confident.

09:24.831 --> 09:27.467
‐ One more hung jury,
and they gotta let me go.

09:27.500 --> 09:28.568
How many times
can you try a person?

09:28.601 --> 09:30.837
‐ Well, we gotta get through
the second trial first.

09:30.870 --> 09:32.939
‐ Well, we already know
how to do that.

09:32.972 --> 09:35.909
‐ Well, if it was just gonna be
the first trial again,

09:35.942 --> 09:37.310
you'd be right, but it won't.

09:37.343 --> 09:38.411
‐ How different can it be?

09:38.445 --> 09:41.314
They gave us their best shot
and you already saw it.

09:41.347 --> 09:44.317
‐ I saw a tactical
miscalculation, Betty.

09:44.350 --> 09:46.419
And she skipped over
what happened in the bedroom

09:46.453 --> 09:49.355
and she did it as a reaction
to the defense we mounted

09:49.389 --> 09:51.257
and obviously,
I'm glad about that.

09:51.291 --> 09:52.892
But she won't do it twice.

09:52.926 --> 09:54.627
‐ The press and the public know

09:54.661 --> 09:56.663
that the prosecution
couldn't convince a jury.

09:56.696 --> 09:57.797
‐ Yes, right.

09:57.831 --> 10:00.266
And the new jury pool will know
the previous jury hung,

10:00.300 --> 10:02.368
but that means
they also will know

10:02.402 --> 10:04.204
that some wanted to convict.

10:04.237 --> 10:06.239
And the DA's office
is pissed now.

10:06.272 --> 10:07.841
They will go through
those transcripts

10:07.874 --> 10:11.111
with a fine‐toothed comb
for Wells to help her prepare,

10:11.144 --> 10:13.213
especially for questioning you.

10:13.246 --> 10:16.916
‐ [blows raspberry]

10:16.950 --> 10:19.352
Are the boys still coming
to San Diego?

10:19.385 --> 10:20.553
‐ Of course.

10:20.587 --> 10:21.754
I would've told you
if they weren't.

10:21.788 --> 10:24.691
But their lawyer and a social
worker are still coming, too.

10:24.724 --> 10:28.862
‐ Fine, I don't care.
They're still my babies.

10:28.895 --> 10:32.365
Uh, when are we gonna
revisit bail?

10:32.398 --> 10:34.167
‐ Betty‐‐
‐ Jack, you promised!

10:34.200 --> 10:35.535
You promised
you would argue bail.

10:35.568 --> 10:39.606
‐ I will, but they will argue
that you are a double murderer,

10:39.639 --> 10:41.875
a danger to society,
and a flight risk,

10:41.908 --> 10:43.543
and they will win.

10:43.576 --> 10:45.245
‐ They just set bail
for‐‐for‐‐

10:45.278 --> 10:47.013
in Milwaukee,
Jeffrey Dahmer!

10:47.046 --> 10:47.814
I heard it on the radio.

10:47.847 --> 10:50.250
‐ Impossible bail.
A million dollars.

10:50.283 --> 10:52.051
‐ But it was set.

10:54.787 --> 10:56.389
Maybe I should've eaten them.

10:56.422 --> 10:58.925
Maybe then my bail
would've been set, too.

11:03.963 --> 11:06.799
‐ Karen, it's Betty.

11:06.833 --> 11:08.201
Hi.

11:08.234 --> 11:10.470
You know, I escaped.

11:10.503 --> 11:13.273
I escaped and I'm
at the 7‐Eleven on Octavia

11:13.306 --> 11:14.407
and I need you to come get me.

11:14.440 --> 11:16.843
And you gotta come quickly
because I‐‐I'm not‐‐

11:16.876 --> 11:18.011
I'm gonna get recognized.

11:18.044 --> 11:19.913
Janet, I need your help.

11:19.946 --> 11:22.248
Yeah.
[stammers]

11:22.282 --> 11:25.318
I escaped from jail with
these other girls, and they‐‐

11:25.351 --> 11:26.653
yes, and then they all
just disappeared

11:26.686 --> 11:27.820
and they left me here.

11:27.854 --> 11:29.923
Can you please come
get me?

11:29.956 --> 11:32.458
Can you come right now?
Right now?

11:32.492 --> 11:35.962
Right now.

11:35.995 --> 11:36.796
[laughs]

11:36.829 --> 11:38.331
I'll be hiding
behind the dumpster.

11:38.364 --> 11:39.332
Just honk your horn
and I'll run out.

11:39.365 --> 11:41.568
Oh, and can you bring
sunglasses and a hat?

11:41.601 --> 11:44.370
Thank you so much, Marie.

11:44.404 --> 11:45.471
No, of course not.

11:45.505 --> 11:47.040
April Fool's.

11:47.073 --> 11:48.041
I said this country

11:48.074 --> 11:50.577
has to redefine
its definition of a weapon.

11:50.610 --> 11:52.545
I said the law has
to take into account

11:52.579 --> 11:53.780
the differences
between men and women

11:53.813 --> 11:55.782
and their respective power‐‐
men have all of it.

11:55.815 --> 11:57.684
I said, you bet Dan Broderick
was a great lawyer,

11:57.717 --> 11:58.818
that's how he could do
to me what he did.

11:58.851 --> 12:02.021
Joe Blow wouldn't have had
the know‐how or the clout.

12:02.055 --> 12:03.957
I said I represent

12:03.990 --> 12:07.727
the extremes of what can happen
to women in divorce courts.

12:07.760 --> 12:10.029
‐ Ah.

12:10.063 --> 12:11.164
And this airs Sunday night?

12:11.197 --> 12:12.131
‐ Yes.

12:12.165 --> 12:14.901
And next up,
"People" magazine.

12:14.934 --> 12:17.637
‐ Yeah, I wanted
to talk to you about that.

12:17.670 --> 12:18.738
‐ [scoffs]
What do you want to talk about?

12:18.771 --> 12:20.373
‐ I just don't have a
good feeling about it.

12:20.406 --> 12:21.307
‐ Oh, based on
all the interviews

12:21.341 --> 12:22.675
you've done
for "People" magazine?

12:22.709 --> 12:24.010
‐ Based on the reporter

12:24.043 --> 12:25.945
giving me a bad feeling
when we talked.

12:25.979 --> 12:27.981
You expect me to honor
your bad feelings.

12:28.014 --> 12:29.082
‐ I'll take my chances,

12:29.115 --> 12:32.585
and I'll take them with
all the other reporters, too.

12:32.619 --> 12:34.320
‐ Fine, okay.

12:34.354 --> 12:36.089
[inhales deeply]

12:36.122 --> 12:37.357
I want you to read these over.

12:37.390 --> 12:39.692
The transcripts
of you and Wells.

12:39.726 --> 12:41.594
Now she's gonna be more focused
this time.

12:41.628 --> 12:43.329
She's going to be strategic.

12:43.363 --> 12:44.297
She won't forget to ask you

12:44.330 --> 12:46.199
what happened
in that room this time.

12:46.232 --> 12:47.934
‐ [inhales sharply]
‐ Now, she may make mistakes,

12:47.967 --> 12:49.636
but they won't
be the same ones.

12:49.669 --> 12:51.471
You have to be ready.

12:54.040 --> 12:55.675
[binder thumps loudly]

12:56.142 --> 13:00.013
‐ I know how to tell my story,
Jack, 'kay?

13:03.549 --> 13:06.085
And you should trust me.

13:06.119 --> 13:10.490
♪ ♪

13:10.523 --> 13:13.393
‐ Did she have motive?

13:13.426 --> 13:15.795
Absolutely.

13:15.828 --> 13:20.433
Probably the oldest,
most common motive there is.

13:20.466 --> 13:22.468
Hate.

13:22.502 --> 13:25.138
Pure, intense,

13:25.171 --> 13:27.740
obsessive,
jealous hate.

13:29.642 --> 13:32.078
Being scorned,
romantically rejected

13:32.111 --> 13:34.280
is common to both sexes.

13:34.314 --> 13:35.348
Being angry, hurt,

13:35.381 --> 13:38.885
even wanting some kind
of revenge is universal.

13:38.918 --> 13:41.888
Most people put that hurt
and anger behind them.

13:41.921 --> 13:45.124
You will hear how Elisabeth
Broderick chose not to.

13:45.158 --> 13:48.261
That was a choice she made.

13:48.294 --> 13:50.963
That hate became her life

13:50.997 --> 13:53.066
and she is still filled
with it.

13:53.099 --> 13:57.270
‐ To really understand
where we get to, what we value,

13:57.303 --> 14:01.374
how we feel, you have
to look at what's inside.

14:01.407 --> 14:05.611
How all the things that happen
to you intertwine.

14:05.645 --> 14:08.181
To know how
Elisabeth Broderick got here,

14:08.214 --> 14:12.352
you have to see who she is
and who Dan Broderick was.

14:12.385 --> 14:16.923
To understand her life,
how she came to be with him,

14:16.956 --> 14:19.192
the promises

14:19.225 --> 14:22.628
and the dreams they had,

14:22.662 --> 14:24.464
and what happened to them.

14:24.497 --> 14:27.333
[soft dramatic music]

14:27.367 --> 14:28.568
[indistinct chatter]

14:28.601 --> 14:29.535
‐ Obviously,
I don't know what the angle

14:29.569 --> 14:30.737
of your article will be,

14:30.770 --> 14:32.805
but I think them not being
able to reach a verdict

14:32.839 --> 14:35.775
was a sign of total confusion,

14:35.808 --> 14:37.810
which even I have
about this case.

14:37.844 --> 14:41.314
No one‐‐no one‐‐
not me, not anyone,

14:41.347 --> 14:42.982
is gonna vote
for killing someone.

14:43.015 --> 14:46.619
But this story,

14:46.652 --> 14:48.521
it's just such
a desperate situation.

14:48.554 --> 14:50.156
You have people
all over the place.

14:50.189 --> 14:52.992
‐ I mean, I talked to people
in San Diego, La Jolla,

14:53.025 --> 14:54.894
even my driver
from the airport yesterday

14:54.927 --> 14:56.562
knew all about your case.

14:56.596 --> 14:57.997
He called you
"used and abused."

14:58.030 --> 14:58.898
‐ I was not in control

14:58.931 --> 15:02.802
and I'm‐‐I'm not as brave
as people think.

15:02.835 --> 15:05.705
Maybe they just see me as the
first in a generation of women

15:05.738 --> 15:07.907
who are not gonna
destroy themselves

15:07.940 --> 15:11.043
when a man in their lives says,
"You're garbage, I'm through."

15:11.077 --> 15:12.011
‐ One woman in La Jolla said

15:12.044 --> 15:13.946
she thought what you'd done
was important,

15:13.980 --> 15:16.416
that the next Dan Broderick
would think twice,

15:16.449 --> 15:19.819
that sometimes you need
a little prairie justice.

15:19.852 --> 15:22.054
What's Betty Broderick's
opinion?

15:24.457 --> 15:26.359
‐ You know I can't answer that.

15:30.863 --> 15:33.065
But you know
what the answer is?

15:40.139 --> 15:43.342
[soft dramatic music]

15:43.443 --> 15:45.344
‐ [indistinct]

15:45.478 --> 15:46.446
♪ ♪

15:46.546 --> 15:50.183
‐ Here.
Right through there.

15:52.351 --> 15:54.253
‐ Hey, guys!

15:56.522 --> 15:58.157
Hey.

15:58.191 --> 16:00.493
Oh, you're all dressed up.

16:05.031 --> 16:06.432
You want a hug?

16:09.836 --> 16:11.003
Maybe later.

16:11.037 --> 16:13.773
Come sit down.

16:13.806 --> 16:15.341
Sit down.

16:24.016 --> 16:26.853
I wrote down all my questions.
Is that silly?

16:26.886 --> 16:27.687
I just don't want to forget

16:27.720 --> 16:29.989
to ask you anything
about your life.

16:34.026 --> 16:38.297
You guys are so tall.
You got so tall.

16:41.667 --> 16:43.669
‐ Was that bedroom
to the right at the top

16:43.703 --> 16:45.137
the first one you went into?

16:45.171 --> 16:47.340
‐ Yes.

16:47.373 --> 16:50.977
‐ And what did you find?

16:51.010 --> 16:53.246
‐ I saw both of the bodies.

16:53.279 --> 16:55.081
‐ What did you do
when you saw them?

16:55.114 --> 16:58.117
‐ I ran over, got down by Dan,

16:58.150 --> 17:01.254
put my hand on his throat
for a pulse.

17:01.287 --> 17:03.122
It was cold.

17:03.155 --> 17:06.092
I felt Linda's throat,
the side of it,

17:06.125 --> 17:08.494
she was cold, too,
with no pulse.

17:09.896 --> 17:12.298
‐ Did you see a phone
in the bedroom?

17:12.331 --> 17:16.369
‐ No, I had seen a phone
on the floor in the hall

17:16.402 --> 17:17.803
as I came up the stairs.

17:17.837 --> 17:19.906
I ran by it.
I didn't know why it was there.

17:19.939 --> 17:21.040
‐ Did you attempt
to call out on it?

17:21.073 --> 17:24.710
‐ No, I could tell my looking
the wire was shredded.

17:24.744 --> 17:25.845
It‐‐it wasn't going to work.

17:25.878 --> 17:27.813
‐ So you went to leave
the house to call the police,

17:27.847 --> 17:31.183
but they were already arriving
there, is that correct?

17:31.217 --> 17:34.320
‐ Yes, there were
officers walking in.

17:34.353 --> 17:38.658
I said,
"The people who live inside‐‐

17:38.691 --> 17:40.459
"they are upstairs.

17:40.493 --> 17:43.596
"They are...

17:43.629 --> 17:46.432
"both dead.

17:46.465 --> 17:47.667
I'll show you."

17:47.700 --> 17:50.636
‐ How would you describe how
she felt about Dan and Linda?

17:50.670 --> 17:51.571
‐ She hated them.

17:51.604 --> 17:54.140
‐ On a scale of one to ten?
‐ Over ten.

17:54.173 --> 17:56.742
[inhales deeply]
Ten‐plus‐plus.

17:56.776 --> 17:58.978
‐ I told her
she was losing friends.

17:59.011 --> 18:01.881
‐ She was getting boring.
No one really cared.

18:01.914 --> 18:04.817
And she should redirect,
refocus.

18:04.850 --> 18:07.219
‐ Did she ever actually
do that?

18:08.854 --> 18:10.156
‐ No.

18:10.189 --> 18:11.991
‐ I had a party
at the beach house.

18:12.024 --> 18:14.160
I had some friends, my family,

18:14.193 --> 18:16.862
and I kind of begged her
to keep her mouth shut

18:16.896 --> 18:19.465
about this divorce, but
we couldn't get her to let go.

18:19.498 --> 18:22.802
It was rude and everyone
was sick of it.

18:22.835 --> 18:26.005
‐ All I know is that
she wanted those children

18:26.038 --> 18:28.574
and she was trying
to gain control of her life

18:28.608 --> 18:31.177
to get it back in order
so that she could have them.

18:31.210 --> 18:33.679
‐ She told you about
taking the children over

18:33.713 --> 18:36.115
and giving them
to Dan, correct?

18:36.148 --> 18:38.184
‐ She never would've
given up those children

18:38.217 --> 18:40.186
if she thought
that he would take them.

18:40.219 --> 18:44.490
She used it as a ploy to make
him assume some responsibility

18:44.523 --> 18:46.559
which he had never had
with those kids.

18:46.592 --> 18:48.194
‐ But she did say,

18:48.227 --> 18:50.796
"He's out there
having a great single life,

18:50.830 --> 18:54.066
why should I take care of the
kids while he's out playing?"

18:54.100 --> 18:58.004
‐ Yes, but I understood
why she said that.

18:58.037 --> 18:59.772
It was very obvious to me.

18:59.805 --> 19:01.507
‐ Did she describe
what her attitude was

19:01.540 --> 19:03.509
about being in jail?

19:03.542 --> 19:05.711
‐ I don't think jail was
too traumatic.

19:05.745 --> 19:08.014
I don't remember
being concerned.

19:08.047 --> 19:10.750
‐ Just that she had gone
to jail.

19:10.783 --> 19:12.385
‐ Spent three days, five days,

19:12.418 --> 19:15.488
and it just didn't seem
to be a problem.

19:15.521 --> 19:18.224
‐ She kind of related it
to being at summer camp.

19:18.257 --> 19:20.726
Away from everyone,
away from everything.

19:20.760 --> 19:21.861
‐ Can you describe

19:21.894 --> 19:24.864
how she would talk about the
children's' father and Linda

19:24.897 --> 19:25.931
in front of the children?

19:25.965 --> 19:28.601
‐ In the same terms.

19:28.634 --> 19:33.539
She always referred to them
using the same vulgar names.

19:33.572 --> 19:35.741
‐ Was that often,
or was that occasional?

19:35.775 --> 19:38.577
‐ All of the time,
all of the time.

19:38.611 --> 19:41.047
‐ Did you talk to her
about not doing it?

19:41.080 --> 19:43.215
‐ She kind of
shrugged her shoulders.

19:43.249 --> 19:45.217
Said, "That is what they are."

19:45.251 --> 19:48.287
‐ She worshipped money.
It was her main goal in life.

19:48.320 --> 19:49.722
She loved it more
than her children.

19:49.755 --> 19:52.525
She's a very materialistic
person, always was.

19:52.558 --> 19:54.560
An alcoholic spender.

19:54.593 --> 19:57.863
‐ So pretty much
a fairly disgusting person

19:57.897 --> 20:00.599
whose main concern was money.

20:00.633 --> 20:02.401
Very few redeeming qualities,

20:02.435 --> 20:05.571
and yet for whatever reason,
this was your friend.

20:05.604 --> 20:06.906
Nothing more.

20:06.939 --> 20:09.942
‐ Did you ever hear her use the
words, "kill" or "threaten?"

20:09.975 --> 20:10.776
‐ Yes.

20:10.810 --> 20:12.878
‐ Can you explain
those circumstances?

20:12.912 --> 20:14.346
‐ That same context of,

20:14.380 --> 20:15.915
what can you do,
you are trapped,

20:15.948 --> 20:18.417
you are the person
who can't get out

20:18.451 --> 20:21.721
and every time you turn,
the system puts you in a corner

20:21.754 --> 20:22.988
and the frustration was such

20:23.022 --> 20:25.124
she would say,
"I'm going to kill 'em."

20:25.157 --> 20:27.560
And I just sort of
had to nod my head.

20:27.593 --> 20:28.494
‐ I saw her in person

20:28.527 --> 20:31.097
I would say probably
three times a week.

20:31.130 --> 20:32.665
And I talked with her
probably every day.

20:32.698 --> 20:35.601
‐ At the time you met her,
did she‐‐

20:35.634 --> 20:39.905
was there an overriding emotion
you would see with her?

20:39.939 --> 20:41.440
‐ I saw a veil of depression

20:41.474 --> 20:43.275
that seemed to be with Betty
the whole time I knew her.

20:43.309 --> 20:45.444
‐ Can you describe her,
emotionally,

20:45.478 --> 20:47.580
in the months preceding
November 5, 1989?

20:47.613 --> 20:50.049
‐ She seemed to be a person
that was giving up on herself.

20:50.082 --> 20:51.517
‐ Did she say anything
on that call

20:51.550 --> 20:54.120
about why she killed
Dan and Linda?

20:54.153 --> 20:58.124
‐ Linda was destroying her
family, destroying her life.

20:58.157 --> 21:02.328
I said back to her,
"So you destroyed her?"

21:03.129 --> 21:05.131
She said, "Yes."

21:05.164 --> 21:07.266
‐ Did she laugh?

21:07.299 --> 21:10.469
‐ [scoffs softly]
Yes.

21:10.503 --> 21:14.273
♪ ♪

21:14.306 --> 21:17.109
‐ Do you remember how your
family was before they split?

21:17.143 --> 21:20.212
How did it‐‐
‐ Objection, beyond the scope.

21:20.246 --> 21:22.481
‐ Overruled.
You can answer it.

21:25.451 --> 21:27.019
‐ Before my parents separated,

21:27.052 --> 21:30.055
I thought we had
a really happy family.

21:30.089 --> 21:32.758
‐ He treated us really well.

21:36.195 --> 21:39.298
He wasn't...

21:39.331 --> 21:44.103
good at the fathering thing
at first, but...

21:44.136 --> 21:46.272
he got better.

21:48.574 --> 21:53.979
He didn't know how
to show his emotions and stuff.

21:54.013 --> 21:56.982
I mean, he wasn't perfect,

21:57.016 --> 21:59.885
but he was a really good dad.

21:59.919 --> 22:01.687
[sniffles]

22:01.720 --> 22:04.423
And he tried really hard.

22:04.456 --> 22:09.361
‐ Did you have any question
in your mind that he loved you?

22:11.931 --> 22:13.732
‐ I knew he did.

22:13.766 --> 22:15.067
‐ I can't make this stop.

22:15.100 --> 22:17.069
I couldn't even stand up.

22:17.102 --> 22:19.505
♪ ♪

22:19.538 --> 22:24.877
I just didn't know where to go,
who to call, or‐‐

22:24.910 --> 22:28.080
I just didn't know what to do,
so I just left the house.

22:28.113 --> 22:31.050
There was so much going on,
these...

22:31.083 --> 22:33.919
crazy thoughts, this anguish.

22:33.953 --> 22:36.956
My eyeballs were turned around
inside of my head.

22:36.989 --> 22:39.425
♪ ♪

22:39.458 --> 22:42.628
The whole world
was inside my head.

22:42.661 --> 22:46.198
I was going to go
to the beach and do it.

22:46.232 --> 22:49.268
I had no life left, anyway.

22:49.301 --> 22:51.604
‐ Did you end up going
to the beach?

22:51.637 --> 22:58.577
♪ ♪

22:59.845 --> 23:04.083
‐ I left the house
to go to the beach, but...

23:04.116 --> 23:11.156
♪ ♪

23:11.190 --> 23:14.293
I never went to the beach, no.

23:14.326 --> 23:17.263
[tense music]

23:23.836 --> 23:24.169
[dramatic music]

23:26.338 --> 23:28.707
♪ ♪

23:28.741 --> 23:30.142
‐ "Asshole,

23:30.175 --> 23:33.312
"Jenjen told me
you're afraid of me.

23:33.345 --> 23:35.147
"You better damn well
be afraid of me

23:35.180 --> 23:37.116
if you keep pulling shit
like this."

23:37.149 --> 23:38.150
‐ Well‐‐[chuckles]

23:38.183 --> 23:40.119
around the time of the wedding,
she told me that.

23:40.152 --> 23:41.387
[stutters]
I made a joke.

23:41.420 --> 23:42.655
‐ You thought it was funny?

23:42.688 --> 23:44.223
‐ Dan Broderick
was never afraid of me.

23:44.256 --> 23:45.557
‐ How many times was it
you re‐read

23:45.591 --> 23:47.626
this Marriage Encounter book?

23:47.660 --> 23:50.195
‐ Over the years?
‐ In 1989.

23:50.229 --> 23:53.966
‐ I'm, I‐‐

23:53.999 --> 23:55.434
a lot, I've read it a lot.

23:55.467 --> 23:57.102
‐ This was
the Marriage Encounter

23:57.136 --> 23:58.337
that Dan had written to you

23:58.370 --> 24:01.240
about what you felt were the
promises he had made to you‐‐

24:01.273 --> 24:02.741
promises that he had broken.

24:02.775 --> 24:03.575
‐ Yes.

24:03.609 --> 24:06.178
‐ So 1989 was
the 20th anniversary

24:06.211 --> 24:08.213
of your wedding
to Dan Broderick,

24:08.247 --> 24:10.249
and the weekend
of November 5th,

24:10.282 --> 24:11.483
when you killed him,

24:11.517 --> 24:13.786
was the anniversary of your
Marriage Encounter,

24:13.819 --> 24:16.822
which was also on
November 5th, correct?

24:16.855 --> 24:17.623
‐ Yes.

24:17.656 --> 24:18.624
‐ Was that something
you recognized

24:18.657 --> 24:21.126
as you re‐read this
Marriage Encounter book

24:21.160 --> 24:22.861
shortly before you killed them?

24:22.895 --> 24:24.430
‐ No.

24:24.463 --> 24:25.230
‐ Where were you
when you made the decision

24:25.264 --> 24:27.499
to not go to the beach,

24:27.533 --> 24:29.335
but to go to Dan Broderick's
house instead?

24:29.368 --> 24:32.004
‐ I don't know.
‐ But you made the decision.

24:32.037 --> 24:35.474
You wanted to go to his house
to blow your brains out.

24:35.507 --> 24:37.209
‐ Well, there were
so many thoughts

24:37.242 --> 24:38.944
going on in my head
at the time.

24:38.978 --> 24:40.379
‐ When was it you checked

24:40.412 --> 24:42.548
to make sure the gun
was still inside your purse

24:42.581 --> 24:44.550
so that you could
blow your brains out?

24:44.583 --> 24:46.218
‐ No, the gun
was always inside the purse.

24:46.251 --> 24:48.954
If the purse was there,
the gun was there.

24:48.988 --> 24:51.590
‐ You found a set of keys.

24:51.623 --> 24:54.126
It didn't occur to you
that these were Tracy's,

24:54.159 --> 24:56.295
who had lost her keys?

24:56.328 --> 24:58.230
‐ Nobody was missing keys.

24:58.263 --> 25:00.699
‐ And so you felt
by breaking in

25:00.733 --> 25:04.970
and confronting him in his
bedroom at 5:00 in the morning,

25:05.004 --> 25:06.705
he was gonna be inclined
to give you what you wanted.

25:06.739 --> 25:08.407
‐ He was gonna be inclined
to listen to me.

25:08.440 --> 25:09.675
‐ And in fact,
that's what you testified

25:09.708 --> 25:11.043
as to why you took the gun,
right?

25:11.076 --> 25:13.178
It had nothing to do
at this point

25:13.212 --> 25:14.413
with wanting to kill yourself.

25:14.446 --> 25:16.648
‐ I took the gun
inside the house

25:16.682 --> 25:18.851
so that he would listen to me.

25:18.884 --> 25:21.553
If he wouldn't listen, then
I was going to kill myself.

25:21.587 --> 25:22.755
‐ You went to the back
of the house

25:22.788 --> 25:25.758
so you could sneak up
on him, correct?

25:25.791 --> 25:29.228
‐ I know I had the sensation
of screaming.

25:29.261 --> 25:33.065
I don't know if I screamed,
"stop" or "no"

25:33.098 --> 25:35.801
or if I just screamed,
or if no sound came out.

25:35.834 --> 25:37.136
It was just a sensation.

25:37.169 --> 25:41.106
‐ You never testified last time
about any sensation, did you?

25:41.140 --> 25:42.341
‐ Well, you never asked me
about anything

25:42.374 --> 25:43.409
that went on
in that room last year.

25:43.442 --> 25:45.010
‐ You never testified
about on the drive there

25:45.044 --> 25:47.513
feeling like your eyeballs
were turned backwards,

25:47.546 --> 25:50.149
the whole world
inside your head, did you?

25:50.182 --> 25:51.116
‐ It's the same story,

25:51.150 --> 25:52.184
maybe I'm just
explaining it better this year.

25:52.217 --> 25:53.285
‐ Maybe you're
embellishing it better.

25:53.318 --> 25:58.023
‐ Objection, Your Honor.
‐ Sustained. Argumentative.

26:03.662 --> 26:07.599
‐ I walked into the room.

26:07.633 --> 26:09.301
I testified that it was dark

26:09.334 --> 26:12.371
because that's
how it appeared to me.

26:14.873 --> 26:17.476
I moved, they moved,
and the gun went off.

26:17.509 --> 26:20.446
Just when I tensed,
like that.

26:20.479 --> 26:22.247
I don't remember
pulling the trigger

26:22.281 --> 26:24.283
once, twice, three, four.

26:24.316 --> 26:27.486
I don't remember
pulling the trigger at all.

26:27.519 --> 26:30.289
‐ This was not an automatic.

26:30.322 --> 26:32.257
This was a revolver.

26:32.291 --> 26:34.293
You have to pull
the trigger each time

26:34.326 --> 26:36.428
in order to shoot the gun.

26:36.462 --> 26:39.331
So you're saying you just

26:39.364 --> 26:42.434
tensed, like that, once?

26:42.468 --> 26:45.070
‐ Yes, and it just went off.

26:45.104 --> 26:47.806
‐ And then you just
tensed like this twice,

26:47.840 --> 26:50.676
and then you just tensed
like that three times,

26:50.709 --> 26:53.479
and then you just tensed
like that four times?

26:53.512 --> 26:55.781
[tense music]

27:00.052 --> 27:02.654
‐ Uh, it must've been
in my right hand.

27:02.688 --> 27:04.323
‐ And when you entered
the room,

27:04.356 --> 27:07.192
how were you holding the gun?

27:07.226 --> 27:08.760
‐ [sighs softly]

27:09.461 --> 27:11.430
‐ I would assume it was
at my side.

27:11.463 --> 27:12.598
‐ Okay.

27:12.631 --> 27:14.433
So when Linda moved,

27:14.466 --> 27:17.035
you had to bring that gun up

27:17.069 --> 27:19.271
and point it at her
in order to shoot her, right?

27:19.304 --> 27:21.507
This tensing reflex action

27:21.540 --> 27:23.675
didn't make the gun go off
in the floor, did it?

27:23.709 --> 27:26.778
And after you tensed once
and shot Linda,

27:26.812 --> 27:30.215
you then had to change your aim
in order to shoot Dan.

27:30.249 --> 27:32.451
Dan was not in the same
position Linda was in

27:32.484 --> 27:34.620
when you shot her, was he?

27:36.321 --> 27:37.856
‐ I didn't see them.
It was dark.

27:37.890 --> 27:40.192
‐ Are you denying you had
to change your aim

27:40.225 --> 27:41.593
in order to shoot Dan?

27:41.627 --> 27:43.028
'Cause he's on the other side
of the bed.

27:43.061 --> 27:46.165
‐ I did not change aim.
I did not move.

27:46.198 --> 27:48.967
I did not move the gun.

27:49.001 --> 27:51.170
‐ You never intended
to kill yourself

27:51.203 --> 27:52.905
with any of those five shots

27:52.938 --> 27:57.009
pointed at Dan and Linda
in the bed, correct?

28:02.614 --> 28:03.549
‐ I thought about it after,

28:03.582 --> 28:06.084
but there weren't
any bullets left in the gun.

28:06.118 --> 28:09.087
‐ Well, you had testified
you were going to confront him

28:09.121 --> 28:11.590
and if it didn't work, you
were going to kill yourself.

28:11.623 --> 28:14.092
Now, obviously if they're
rolling away from you

28:14.126 --> 28:15.994
yelling, "Call the police,"

28:16.028 --> 28:18.897
the confrontation
isn't working.

28:18.931 --> 28:21.934
But that gun never made it
up to your head, did it?

28:21.967 --> 28:25.671
That gun only went
to their bodies, didn't it?

28:28.106 --> 28:29.174
After you shot them,

28:29.208 --> 28:32.077
you didn't immediately
leave the room, did you?

28:32.110 --> 28:32.978
‐ Yes, I did.

28:33.011 --> 28:35.247
‐ That's not the
immediate thing you did

28:35.280 --> 28:36.715
after shooting them, was it?

28:36.748 --> 28:39.685
[soft dramatic music]

28:39.718 --> 28:42.020
♪ ♪

28:42.054 --> 28:45.424
‐ I went to get the phone.
‐ Okay.

28:45.457 --> 28:47.526
You had to walk
all around the bed

28:47.559 --> 28:49.628
where Dan
is lying on the floor.

28:49.661 --> 28:51.863
You had to walk
through this area

28:51.897 --> 28:56.602
to grab the phone
and pull it out of the wall,

28:56.635 --> 28:59.871
didn't you?

29:01.873 --> 29:03.408
You indicated this morning

29:03.442 --> 29:07.613
that you'd not been able to
tell anyone how sorry you were.

29:07.646 --> 29:09.815
Isn't it true that
since you've been in jail,

29:09.848 --> 29:12.951
you've written hundreds
of letters?

29:12.985 --> 29:13.919
‐ Maybe over the whole time.

29:13.952 --> 29:17.990
‐ Many letters every day
to friends, family,

29:18.023 --> 29:20.225
newspaper reporters,
celebrities.

29:20.259 --> 29:21.994
There wasn't anything
preventing you

29:22.027 --> 29:23.662
from talking
about your feelings

29:23.695 --> 29:24.763
in any of these letters,
was there?

29:24.796 --> 29:28.800
‐ I've testified I wasn't free
to express any feelings

29:28.834 --> 29:31.970
because I knew the letters were
copied going in and going out.

29:32.004 --> 29:34.006
‐ You wrote a letter
to Amy Wallace

29:34.039 --> 29:37.175
at the "Los Angeles Times"
from jail, correct?

29:37.209 --> 29:38.043
‐ Correct.

29:38.076 --> 29:39.978
‐ "You have the general idea,

29:40.012 --> 29:42.180
"but the chronology and facts
are all twisted.

29:42.214 --> 29:46.818
I'll call, we'll talk.
Only I know the whole truth."

29:46.852 --> 29:49.187
‐ I was just correcting
her article.

29:49.221 --> 29:52.257
I wouldn't have expressed
the feelings I'm talking about

29:52.291 --> 29:53.358
with a newspaper reporter.

29:53.392 --> 29:56.962
‐ You made a specific
correction with Amy Wallace.

29:56.995 --> 29:58.930
You indicated Jennifer
had testified

29:58.964 --> 30:00.599
that you said Dan had said,

30:00.632 --> 30:04.269
"Okay, okay,
you shot me, I'm dead."

30:04.303 --> 30:07.673
You told Amy Wallace
no, that's not right.

30:07.706 --> 30:11.677
He said,
"Okay, you got me. I'm dead."

30:11.710 --> 30:12.577
Right?
‐ Right.

30:12.611 --> 30:14.780
‐ Didn't you just testify
earlier today

30:14.813 --> 30:17.215
that you don't remember him
saying anything?

30:17.249 --> 30:18.417
‐ What I testified to today

30:18.450 --> 30:21.953
is that I don't really know
what happened in that room.

30:21.987 --> 30:23.288
It was‐‐
it was flashes of things‐‐

30:23.322 --> 30:25.223
‐ Excuse me.
You answered the question.

30:25.257 --> 30:26.291
Let me just ask you this.

30:26.325 --> 30:29.761
If you don't remember what
happened in that room,

30:29.795 --> 30:32.064
how could you correct
the "Los Angeles Times"

30:32.097 --> 30:33.899
about what happened
in that room?

30:33.932 --> 30:37.135
[soft tense music]

30:37.169 --> 30:39.671
♪ ♪

30:39.705 --> 30:43.141
You wrote another letter
to a friend

30:43.175 --> 30:47.813
where you said,
"Whatever the future holds,

30:47.846 --> 30:50.015
"I'll be okay.

30:50.048 --> 30:54.319
"I've chosen the path of peace,

30:54.353 --> 30:56.588
and I finally have it."

30:56.621 --> 31:02.928
♪ ♪

31:02.961 --> 31:07.032
‐ I don't remember
saying that, but...

31:09.701 --> 31:13.038
yes, it's been more peaceful
for me‐‐

31:13.071 --> 31:14.539
[sniffles]

31:14.573 --> 31:16.575
being in jail.

31:16.608 --> 31:18.844
‐ No further questions.

31:18.877 --> 31:24.449
♪ ♪

31:24.483 --> 31:27.719
‐ Anyone can see that
she doesn't know who she is.

31:28.820 --> 31:32.324
How much she wants
to please people.

31:34.326 --> 31:38.096
And how hungry she is

31:38.130 --> 31:39.030
for love.

31:40.265 --> 31:42.100
‐ If those tapes
of Betty and her kids

31:42.134 --> 31:44.803
don't prove she went nuts,
then what does?

31:44.836 --> 31:47.439
She's sick.
She needs help.

31:50.008 --> 31:55.480
‐ But you know, I don't know
if she can get well.

31:55.514 --> 31:57.082
Not now.

31:59.418 --> 32:02.921
I think she just needs
to get old.

32:07.292 --> 32:08.059
‐ It's okay to have
an emotional response

32:09.428 --> 32:11.897
to this case.

32:11.930 --> 32:14.199
You may find you disagree
with each other,

32:14.232 --> 32:17.402
maybe passionately,
about your feelings.

32:17.436 --> 32:19.304
I think you should acknowledge
those feelings.

32:19.337 --> 32:21.840
Get them out and then
when you're done feeling,

32:21.873 --> 32:24.676
it's time to start thinking

32:24.709 --> 32:27.012
because that
is why you are here.

32:27.045 --> 32:30.749
‐ If you think of
the people you live with,

32:30.782 --> 32:32.851
they see everything about you.

32:32.884 --> 32:35.554
Your worst and your best.

32:35.587 --> 32:38.890
The habits that you
wouldn't dare show the public.

32:38.924 --> 32:40.659
You give them who you are.

32:40.692 --> 32:44.796
‐ I'll concede, Dan Broderick
was wrong in leaving his wife.

32:44.830 --> 32:46.731
[soft tense music]

32:46.765 --> 32:48.433
No men should ever
leave their wives.

32:48.467 --> 32:50.669
All marriages
should be blissfully happy.

32:50.702 --> 32:52.704
‐ I'm wearing a suit.

32:52.737 --> 32:55.440
For you, there's no telling
how I dress at home.

32:55.474 --> 32:59.444
What I do, what I'm like
when I feel good or bad.

32:59.478 --> 33:01.847
♪ ♪

33:01.880 --> 33:02.714
But she knows.

33:02.747 --> 33:04.015
‐ I'll concede,

33:04.049 --> 33:06.785
Dan Broderick should've given
Elisabeth Broderick more money.

33:06.818 --> 33:09.554
He should've given her
everything she demanded.

33:09.588 --> 33:12.257
But that assumes
it would've mattered.

33:12.290 --> 33:14.559
Would another closet full
of clothes

33:14.593 --> 33:17.562
with the tags still hanging
on them have made a difference?

33:19.564 --> 33:23.568
I'll concede, Dan Broderick
should've given her the kids

33:23.602 --> 33:25.303
every time she asked for them

33:25.337 --> 33:27.038
no matter what
she was doing to them,

33:27.072 --> 33:28.440
no matter that she had

33:28.473 --> 33:30.542
handed them over to him
in the first place.

33:30.575 --> 33:32.043
I'll concede,

33:32.077 --> 33:34.212
Linda Kolkena should
never have gotten involved

33:34.246 --> 33:35.914
with Dan Broderick.

33:35.947 --> 33:37.549
Should never have loved him,
married him.

33:37.582 --> 33:41.052
Should never have responded
to Elisabeth Broderick's venom.

33:41.086 --> 33:42.320
She should've been perfect.

33:42.354 --> 33:45.257
And she wasn't.
And neither was Dan.

33:45.290 --> 33:48.393
But the verdict forms you'll
be filling out do not read,

33:48.426 --> 33:51.730
"We the jury find Dan and Linda
Broderick were perfect people."

33:51.763 --> 33:54.633
‐ And that's what hurts.

33:54.666 --> 33:57.969
I trust that you are with me.

33:58.003 --> 34:01.673
I'm giving you who I am.

34:01.706 --> 34:06.077
When you break that trust,
that should bother you.

34:06.111 --> 34:08.947
That should hurt.

34:08.980 --> 34:12.851
Your betrayal
of someone who was there.

34:12.884 --> 34:16.955
♪ ♪

34:16.988 --> 34:18.356
But then you find

34:18.390 --> 34:21.493
that is probably the history
of the world.

34:21.526 --> 34:23.528
Just the way people
look at things.

34:23.562 --> 34:27.999
‐ "Whatever the future holds,
I'll be okay.

34:28.033 --> 34:31.870
I have chosen the path
of peace."

34:31.903 --> 34:37.309
♪ ♪

34:37.342 --> 34:39.544
Killing two people,

34:39.578 --> 34:43.848
including the father
of her children,

34:43.882 --> 34:46.618
gave Elisabeth Broderick peace.

34:46.651 --> 34:51.489
♪ ♪

34:51.856 --> 34:52.958
[hammer clicks]

34:52.991 --> 34:54.526
[screaming]
‐ Call the police!

34:54.559 --> 34:57.729
‐ When you commit a crime
that is inherently dangerous,

34:57.762 --> 35:01.266
when you bring a loaded gun
into a house,

35:01.299 --> 35:03.868
there is a danger
that someone will get hurt,

35:03.902 --> 35:05.337
someone will get killed.

35:05.370 --> 35:07.472
But if you say
at that point in time,

35:07.505 --> 35:10.809
"I believe there was
a reasonable doubt

35:10.842 --> 35:14.145
as to intent to kill,"

35:14.179 --> 35:16.681
that is
involuntary manslaughter.

35:18.116 --> 35:21.319
If you say I believe
there was the intent to kill,

35:21.353 --> 35:24.656
but the person was acting
on emotion,

35:24.689 --> 35:27.025
acting on what
they had been through?

35:27.058 --> 35:28.827
Ladies and gentlemen,

35:28.860 --> 35:33.231
that is voluntary manslaughter.

35:33.264 --> 35:37.569
‐ The judge said this
is not a death penalty case.

35:37.602 --> 35:38.603
That is not true.

35:38.637 --> 35:41.940
Elisabeth Broderick imposed
the death penalty

35:41.973 --> 35:43.141
on Dan and Linda.

35:43.174 --> 35:45.844
They didn't get to present
their case in front of a jury

35:45.877 --> 35:47.512
before she executed them.

35:48.947 --> 35:52.517
She made that decision
on her own.

35:52.550 --> 35:56.221
Being hurt doesn't give you
the right to do that.

35:56.254 --> 36:00.558
Justice calls that
first‐degree murder.

36:08.099 --> 36:08.333
[door buzzes]

36:09.834 --> 36:13.004
‐ Hmm, hmm.

36:13.038 --> 36:15.407
‐ Don't cheat.

36:15.440 --> 36:18.476
‐ I didn't.
‐ You were about to.

36:19.244 --> 36:20.445
‐ Let's see.

36:20.478 --> 36:22.614
[door opens]

36:22.647 --> 36:25.583
[tense music]

36:25.617 --> 36:32.757
♪ ♪

36:36.594 --> 36:38.830
‐ We, the jury
in the above entitled cause,

36:38.863 --> 36:42.033
find the defendant,
Elisabeth Anne Broderick,

36:42.067 --> 36:44.569
guilty of the crime of murder,

36:44.602 --> 36:48.139
felony as charged in count one
of the information.

36:48.173 --> 36:51.409
And set the degree thereof
as murder in the second degree,

36:51.443 --> 36:53.778
victim Daniel Broderick.

36:53.812 --> 36:56.081
We, the jury
in the above entitled cause,

36:56.114 --> 36:58.283
by the defendant,
Elisabeth Anne Broderick,

36:58.316 --> 37:00.685
guilty of the crime of murder,

37:00.719 --> 37:04.422
a felony as charged in
count two of the information

37:04.456 --> 37:07.792
and set the degree of thereof
as murder in the second degree,

37:07.826 --> 37:11.663
victim Linda Broderick.

37:11.696 --> 37:13.565
Ladies and gentlemen
of the jury,

37:13.598 --> 37:16.101
are these your verdicts
as I read them?

37:18.303 --> 37:20.638
‐ Yes.

37:20.672 --> 37:22.774
It was clear
right from the beginning

37:22.807 --> 37:24.642
that another mistrial
was possible.

37:24.676 --> 37:26.745
One juror right off said that

37:26.778 --> 37:28.012
she would never vote
for first degree.

37:28.046 --> 37:30.815
She would hang the jury
before she ever did that.

37:30.849 --> 37:34.219
‐ For four days, they shouted
their heads off at me,

37:34.252 --> 37:37.122
but I just didn't believe
that Betty went in with malice.

37:37.155 --> 37:38.923
He flipped her out.

37:38.957 --> 37:41.626
He killed her first‐‐
her spirit.

37:41.659 --> 37:43.628
And that's just
how it appeared to me.

37:43.661 --> 37:45.630
‐ People were yelling, crying.

37:45.663 --> 37:47.966
Until lunch today even,
there were still holdouts.

37:47.999 --> 37:49.434
‐ So how did you
reach a decision?

37:49.467 --> 37:52.036
‐ Uh, we, um,

37:52.070 --> 37:54.806
listened to that
one phone call again.

37:54.839 --> 37:57.308
Betty with her son,
who was crying.

37:57.342 --> 37:59.811
We all held hands and, uh...

38:01.679 --> 38:03.214
we just got there.

38:03.248 --> 38:06.351
‐ I mean, I've been around
the corner once or twice.

38:06.384 --> 38:08.987
I know what pain feels like.

38:09.020 --> 38:11.156
As a woman,
you have to bear a lot of it

38:11.189 --> 38:13.391
or you are just lost
from the beginning.

38:13.424 --> 38:16.628
What I did for Betty
was the right thing for Betty.

38:16.661 --> 38:17.796
Second degree.

38:17.829 --> 38:20.131
She'll be out in four
or five years, don't you think?

38:20.165 --> 38:24.002
‐ Maximum sentence Betty
could get is 32 to life.

38:25.937 --> 38:28.173
‐ No.

38:28.206 --> 38:31.342
No, I‐‐I can't‐‐
I can't believe it.

38:31.376 --> 38:33.011
No, if I thought she was‐‐
if I‐‐

38:33.044 --> 38:35.847
if she was gonna get anything
more, I would've hung in.

38:35.880 --> 38:38.616
And Judge Spiller
won't do that.

38:38.650 --> 38:40.985
No, he's kind.

38:41.019 --> 38:42.921
He'll‐‐I'm sure
he'll be lenient.

38:42.954 --> 38:45.056
I thought he was
just wonderful.

38:47.125 --> 38:51.262
‐ The physical evidence,
which is uncontradicted,

38:51.296 --> 38:55.700
shows she intentionally aimed
at both people.

38:55.733 --> 38:58.703
It's not just the pulling
of the phone out of the wall

38:58.736 --> 39:02.674
but the carrying of it
into the hallway

39:02.707 --> 39:05.376
that shows a high degree
of callousness.

39:05.410 --> 39:07.378
Therefore, the crime
of second‐degree murder

39:07.412 --> 39:11.850
in count two, I'll select
a term of 15 years to life,

39:11.883 --> 39:15.520
consecutive to that imposed
in count one.

39:15.553 --> 39:16.955
[gavel bangs]

39:16.988 --> 39:20.058
[soft dramatic music]

39:20.091 --> 39:27.031
♪ ♪

39:56.327 --> 39:58.830
‐ He was smart and fun
and ambitious,

39:58.863 --> 40:00.965
and so was I.

40:00.999 --> 40:05.169
I don't know what we really
thought of each other.

40:05.203 --> 40:06.905
All I know is

40:06.938 --> 40:09.173
we were exactly what we
thought the other one

40:09.207 --> 40:11.643
was supposed
to be looking for.

40:13.278 --> 40:15.246
Back then?

40:18.683 --> 40:21.286
I remember dancing.

40:21.319 --> 40:24.188
Our songs.

40:24.222 --> 40:29.327
We had songs we would dance to
over and over.

40:29.360 --> 40:30.929
[chuckles]

40:30.962 --> 40:33.097
Great makeout music.

40:37.035 --> 40:42.507
♪ You ask how much I need you ♪

40:42.540 --> 40:48.046
♪ Must I explain? ♪

40:48.079 --> 40:53.851
♪ I need you, oh, my darling ♪

40:53.885 --> 40:59.791
♪ Like roses need rain ♪

40:59.824 --> 41:04.562
♪ You ask
how long I'll love you ♪

41:04.595 --> 41:07.465
[telephone rings]

41:08.066 --> 41:10.335
Hello?

41:10.368 --> 41:11.469
‐ I have bad news.

41:11.502 --> 41:13.838
‐ Oh, well, that's not
the kind I like.

41:13.871 --> 41:15.006
[chuckles]

41:15.039 --> 41:18.009
‐ Coral Reef house is sold.
I'm sorry.

41:18.042 --> 41:19.544
Dan got a court order

41:19.577 --> 41:21.245
and went in front
of a judge this morning.

41:21.279 --> 41:22.880
‐ I understand.

41:24.449 --> 41:26.517
Hey, boys!
Can you come set the table?

41:26.551 --> 41:29.220
As soon as I mash the potatoes,
we'll be ready to eat.

41:29.253 --> 41:32.523
♪ ♪

41:32.557 --> 41:35.360
‐ This is calendar number
three, Broderick v. Broderick.

41:35.393 --> 41:38.262
Mr. Broderick and his
attorney, Douglas Layton,

41:38.296 --> 41:41.165
are present,
as is Elisabeth Broderick

41:41.199 --> 41:43.334
and her attorney,
Robert Munro.

41:43.368 --> 41:45.737
♪ ♪

41:45.770 --> 41:48.673
[indistinct chatter,
phones ringing]

41:48.706 --> 41:51.442
‐ Reception,
how can I help you?

41:51.476 --> 41:53.444
Please hold.

41:53.478 --> 41:55.380
♪ ♪

41:55.413 --> 41:56.848
Can I help you?

41:56.881 --> 41:59.684
‐ I'm Betty.

41:59.717 --> 42:02.553
Mrs. Broderick.

42:02.587 --> 42:08.292
♪ ♪

42:08.326 --> 42:13.064
Wait, wait, wait.
Come back, come back.

42:13.097 --> 42:14.565
We're gonna go home.

42:14.599 --> 42:17.835
♪ ♪

42:17.869 --> 42:22.206
Are you sleeping with her?
‐ [sighs]

42:23.474 --> 42:25.376
‐ Are you?

42:29.580 --> 42:30.748
‐ [sighs]

42:30.782 --> 42:33.584
I'm in love with her.

42:33.618 --> 42:37.622
♪ ♪

42:37.655 --> 42:41.459
‐ ♪ Must I explain ♪

42:43.127 --> 42:48.833
♪ I need you,
oh, my darling ♪

42:48.866 --> 42:53.271
♪ Like roses need rain ♪

42:53.304 --> 42:54.605
♪ ♪

42:54.639 --> 43:00.244
♪ You ask
how long I'll love you ♪

43:00.278 --> 43:05.983
♪ I'll tell you true ♪

43:08.286 --> 43:13.124
♪ Until the twelfth of never ♪

43:14.492 --> 43:17.995
♪ I'll still be ♪

43:18.029 --> 43:19.564
♪ Loving you ♪

43:21.666 --> 43:23.534
Someone else needs this phone.

43:27.805 --> 43:29.941
[door buzzes]

43:33.578 --> 43:34.979
[door slams]
